Could Trump's Tweets Influence the Stock Market?¶

Introduction¶

Today we will look into the data science pipeline, in other words, what is the process by which we do data science?

In order to do so, we will take as an example Donald Trump's tweets. Donald Trump tweeted a lot before he was permanently banned in January of 2021, and in many of those tweets, he mentioned publicly traded companies.

Motivation¶

Were the value of the stocks of these companies influenced in any way by his tweets? This is a very hard question to answer, perhaps impossible today. The reason why is because the stock market is extremely volatile and can be influenced by tons of factors, and Trump's tweets were only one of them.

However, instead of trying to answer this question, it is easier and more reasonable to attempt to prove or disprove the following null hypothesis: "Trump's tweets had no influence in the stock market." How could we determine that?

Proving or Disproving the Hypothesis¶

There is no ideal way prove or disprove the null hypothesis, since when dealing with margins of error, they are different from discipline to discipline. In our case, we will choose a 5% margin of error. This means that, if we see that investing in what Trump tweeted, would've yielded more than a 5% profit than our control (S&P500), then we will feel confident enough to disprove the null hypothesis.

If we disprove the null hypothesis, does that mean that Trump's tweets influenced the stock market? NO! All it means, is that we have enough evidence to say that, it is not the case that Trump's tweets didn't influence the stock market. This distinction is subtle, but important. More information on this subject can be found here.

What we will do¶

We will collect Donald Trump's tweets from September 1st 2016 onwards (until his permanent ban in January 2021), as well as the stock prices of the Top 25 stocks of the S&P500 in 2016. Using all this data, along with Natural Language Processing, we will attempt to determine whether we may or may not disprove the null hypothesis established above. As a control and reference, we will use the S&P500 price throughout the observed time.

In order to do this tutorial, we will follow the Data Science pipeline, which can be seen below.

We will be following these steps closely. Notice that they are not necessarilly linear, as at any given point we might go back to a previous step. The tutorial will follow the following format:

  • Setup
  • Data Collection
  • Data Processing
  • More Data Collection
  • More Data Processing
  • Exploratory phase
  • Analysis and Hypothesis testing
  • Insight and Conclusions

Inspiration: This project has been inspired by Max Brown's Trump2Cash bot. This bot used to work when Trump still had a Twitter account, and would invest in real time depending on whether Trump mentioned a publicly traded company, and whether what he said was positive or negative according to sentiment analysis.

Part 1: Data Collection¶

Getting the Tweets¶

I will be using Trump's Twitter Archive, which has been keeping track of every Tweet by Donald Trump (including deleted ones) since September 2016. It's database has older tweets, but any deleted tweets before this time will not be present.

I will assume that the data in the archive is reputable, and I base that assumption on the following statement in the author's FAQ "[Trump's Twitter Archive ] It's regularly referenced by FactCheck.org, PolitiFact, Snopes, and Wikipedia, along with almost every major news outlet"

I've downloaded the CSV file manually. Sadly, because it is stored in Google Drive, there is no good, easy way of downloading it with Python. You can get it here: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1xRKHaP-QwACMydlDnyFPEaFdtskJuBa6/view. I've saved it manually as "tweets.csv".

NOTE - On missing tweets: As reliable as the archive may be, deleted tweets have were not recorded from before September 2016. However, we do not know exactly when in September the recording of tweets began. Thus, by starting at September 1st, it is highly probable that a few tweets might have been deleted. This is fine, since it should not affect the overall tutorial, but it is important to state and know this.

Getting the Stocks¶

We will be comparing the risk of investing in stocks to some degree, using as a control the price of the S&P 500. We will first get the list of stocks that we might invest in (depending on what Trump tweeted).

Firstly, we'll get all the stocks from Wikipedia, here: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_S%26P_500_companies.

It contains two tables:

  • List of the current S&P500 Companies
  • List of changes that ocurred to the S&P500

Since our analysis takes place from September 1st 2016 onwards, we will keep all stocks that were present before this date. In order to make the analysis simpler, since this is a tutorial, we will also get rid of all stocks that were removed, sometime, after September 1st 2016. The reason why is because these stocks might have been removed for several reasons, including merging and being replaced by others. Thus, in order to not deal with these intricacies, we will disregard them entirely.

We will have to use BeautifulSoup to scrape the data for stocks, since Wikipedia has these two tables in the website as an .html file.

Part 2: Data Processing. Missing Data? Keeping what we need.¶

Processing the Tweets¶

Now that we have collected the data, and we know what each column is doing, it is important to make sure that we have processed and formatted the data so that we can work with it.

One of the biggest things to check is whether we have missing data or not. Are any of the entries for a column missing? Do any of them have a formatting that we don't expect?

Let's check each row to make sure that the data we are looking at is formatted as we expect, and if its not, let's deal with it. The things we care about keeping are the tweet id, its text, date and whether or not it was a retweet, since that is not an original tweet coming from Trump.

In [11]:
# For every row in the table
for index, row in tweets_table.head().iterrows():
    
    # Getting the current values for the row
    tweet_id = row['id']
    tweet_text = row['text']
    is_retweet = row['isRetweet']
    is_deleted = row['isDeleted']
    device = row['device']
    favorites = row['favorites']
    retweets = row['retweets']
    date = row['date']
    isFlagged = row['isFlagged']
    
    row_missing = False
    
    if not isinstance(tweet_id, int):
        row_missing = True
    
    if (not isinstance(tweet_text, str)) or tweet_text == '':
        row_missing = True
        
    if (not isinstance(is_retweet, str)) or (is_retweet != 'f' and is_retweet != 't'):
        row_missing = True
        
    if (not isinstance(date, str)) or date == '':
        row_missing = True
        
    if row_missing:
        print(f"Missing data in row: {row}")
        row_missing = False

It seems no data is missing from what we are interested in, which is great. This is not always the case, and depending on what is missing, we might have to deal with it in different ways.

If the text of the tweet or its date were missing, that would have been an issue and we'd have to ignore that tweet, since we would have no way of determining whether that tweet might have had an effect. If we didn't know whether it was a retweet or not, it might affect us depending on what we choose to do with that information.

For the sake of this tutorial, we'll get rid of all retweets, and just keep the actual tweets. All other data we can get rid of.

def str_to_time(s):
    if pd.isnull(s):
        return pd.NA
    else:
        return datetime.strptime(s,'%Y-%m-%d')

current_sp500['Date first added'] = current_sp500['Date first added'].apply(str_to_time)

Getting the rankings in 2016¶

Since around 500 companies is a lot, and this is a small tutorial, we will limit the amount of comapnies we look at to the top 25 at the time. One way of finding the ranking would've been to calculate it ourselves. The ranking in the index is calculated by the following equation:

$$\text{Weight} = \frac{Company Market Cap}{\text{Total of all market caps}}$$

Source: https://www.investopedia.com/terms/s/sp500.asp

Luckilly, we can get away with looking at a website that ranked it already in 2016. Using archive.org, we can see what the ranking was in August of 2016. It can be found here: https://web.archive.org/web/20160822220709/https://www.slickcharts.com/sp500.

We will have to do a couple minor adjustments to the company list, as

NOTE: I am assuming that the information on the website slickcharts.com, on August 22nd 2016 was accurate. Since I believe the data on the website to be accurate, I will use it. The alternative, is to produce each of the weights and determine the ranking as described before.

In [27]:
# List of companies in order by rank in 2016
# NOTE: I renamed BRK.B to BRK-B to match the Yahoo Finance API
top25 = ['AAPL', 'MSFT', 'XOM', 'JNJ', 'AMZN', 'GE', 'FB', 'CMCSA', 'BRK-B', 'T', 'JPM', 'GOOGL',
         'PG', 'GOOG', 'WFC', 'VZ', 'PFE', 'CVX', 'MRK', 'KO', 'HD', 'INTC', 
         'PEP', 'BAC', 'PM']

for index, row in current_sp500.iterrows():
    symbol = row['Symbol']
    
    # Adding extra case to fix 'BRK-B instead of BRK.B'
    if symbol == 'BRK.B':
        current_sp500.at[index, 'rank'] = (top25.index('BRK-B') + 1)
        current_sp500.at[index, 'Symbol'] = 'BRK-B'
        
    elif symbol in top25:
        current_sp500.at[index, 'rank'] = (top25.index(symbol) + 1)

Back to Part 1: Collecting Stock Data¶

Now that we know what stocks we'd like to analyze, we need to actually get them. We can do this using Yahoo Finance's API to get the historic stock data for the 25 companies we are looking into.

We can download the data for each company using the .download() method. Take for instance how we'd download data for Apple:

apple_data = yf.download('AAPL', start='2016-09-01', end='2021-01-08')

Conveniently, we get back a Pandas dataframe.

We will now download the table for each company we need. Conveniently, yf.download() returns a Pandas Dataframe, whcih is the format we wanted. We will store all of these in a dictionary, where the key is the Ticker for each company.

In [31]:
%%capture
stock_tables = {}

for ticker in top25:
    stock_tables[ticker] = yf.download(ticker, start='2016-09-01', end='2021-01-08')
    
sp500_table = yf.download('^GSPC', start='2016-09-01', end='2021-01-08')

We have now succesfully downloaded all the stock data. The last step in processing it is to change its date from a string to a datetime object. Every date is stored as the name for each row. It is more convenient to have it as a column and datetime object, so we can do the time comparisons in the same way we would do it for every other dated row in other tables.

In [32]:
for key in stock_tables.keys():
    for index, row in stock_tables[key].iterrows():
        stock_tables[key].at[index, 'date'] = pd.to_datetime(row.name)
        
for index, row in sp500_table.iterrows():
    sp500_table.at[index, 'date'] = pd.to_datetime(row.name)

Back to Part 2: Natural Language Processing, and Putting it all Together¶

To recap: We have now collected all of Trump's tweets from September 1st 2016, and all the stock prices from the Top 25 stocks of the S&P500 index at the time (September 1st 2016).

Now, we have to put these two together, in order to answer:

  • In which tweets did Trump mention any of these companies?
  • When he mentioned these companies, were his comments negative, positive or neutral?

Once we have done this, we'll have all the information we need to start asking questions.

Processing the Tweets, Adding Stock Information¶

Now we will check every tweet in our table, and see if mentions a company. We'll make a new table where we can keep the information of the tickers and the tweets. Before doing that however, I will make a list of terms for each company that might show up on the tweets.

As one might expect, it'd be rare for Trump to tweet about companies by their ticker names, or by their full names. It might make sense in the case of "Facebook" or "Amazon", but not so much for "Verizon Communications" (Verizon).

We will do this manually, which is not ideal, but is what we can do in the scope of this tutorial.

What if more than a company is mentioned on a tweet?: We'll add the highest rated company that is mentioned first. This is in order to keep each tweet and ticker on a 1-1 relationship, making our analysis portion easier.

NOTE: How might we do this better? What assumptions are we making?

It is very hard to determine for each particular case, how Trump might have referred to a company. I will manually add a number of regular expressions, which I believe will cover a wide basis of different spellings, but this is in no way perfect. Thus, I am assuming I will get most of them correctly, but it is of course possible that is not the case.

One approach, given more time and resources, would be to write a NLP model designed for this very purpose, that might be able to determine, in context, what strings might refer to what company with more accuracy and flexibility. This is currently not the case, but we can still get insightful results without it.

Now, let's go over every tweet, and see if it matches any of the companies. One potential problem we might ran into is that Google has two different stocks. This in general is fine, but in order to maintain the tutorial simple, we will remove one of them, and we'll assume they are strongly correlated (if one goes up so does the other one).

To also keep it simple, we will assume that each tweet can only refer to a single company.

In [40]:
# Table of all tweets starting on September 1st
for index, row in september_onwards.iterrows():
    tweet_id = row['id']
    tweet = row['text']
    date = row['date']
    
    tweets_and_tickers.at[index, 'tweet_id'] = tweet_id
    tweets_and_tickers.at[index, 'text'] = tweet
    tweets_and_tickers.at[index, 'date'] = date
    
    for ticker in terms_by_ticker.keys():
        if terms_by_ticker[ticker].search(tweet):
            tweets_and_tickers.at[index, 'ticker'] = ticker
            break

Doing Sentiment Analysis, Putting it all Together¶

Consider the following examples

In [49]:
from nltk.sentiment.vader import SentimentIntensityAnalyzer
vader = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()
sample = 'Dog'
sample2 = 'I kind of like my dog'
sample3 = 'I super duper love my dog'
sample4 = 'I hate my cat'
print(vader.polarity_scores(sample))
print(vader.polarity_scores(sample2))
print(vader.polarity_scores(sample3))
print(vader.polarity_scores(sample4))

{'neg': 0.0, 'neu': 1.0, 'pos': 0.0, 'compound': 0.0}
{'neg': 0.0, 'neu': 0.615, 'pos': 0.385, 'compound': 0.3612}
{'neg': 0.0, 'neu': 0.27, 'pos': 0.73, 'compound': 0.8442}
{'neg': 0.649, 'neu': 0.351, 'pos': 0.0, 'compound': -0.5719}

As we can see, scores of 0 are neutral, positive scores mean a positive sentiment (the closer to 1 the more positive) and negative values mean negative sentiment (closer to -1 the worse).

We will now use this on all the tweets that mentioned companies. We will only keep track of the compound score, as we want to know overall if it was positive, neutral or negative.

In [50]:
for index, row in company_tweets.iterrows():
    tweet = row['text']
    scores = vader.polarity_scores(tweet)
    compound = scores['compound']
    company_tweets.at[index, 'sentiment'] = compound

Restricting the Window of Time¶

It is currently hard to see whether we might draw any correlations between Trump's tweets and a raise or fall in the price of a stock. So, let's try using a smaller window of time. By observation, it seems the period from 2018-01 to 2019-01 might be worth investigating, as Amazon's stock seems to have been going up and down considerably. Google's stock remained somewhat more stable during the same period of time, while the other stocks were all over the place, some stable and some not.

In contrast, the S&P500 seems to have had a major dip during the time, so it might yield some interesting results to limit our more in-depth analysis to this window of time.

What now? Part 4: Analysis and Hypothesis Testing.¶

This is not looking promising at all, at least visually. However, there is another thing we might try. Let's run an experiment to see if investing in the stocks that Trump tweeted about positively yielded better results than a control group (such as the S&P500).

We can set up 5 imaginary investors, each with \$100,000. They will operate in the following way:

  • Investor #1: 100% invested in the S&P500
  • Investor #2: 90% invested in the S&P500, 10% in Trump Tweets
  • Investor #3: 80% invested in the S&P500, 20% in Trump Tweets
  • Investor #4: 50% invested in the S&P500, 50% in Trump Tweets
  • Investor #5: 0% invested in the S&P500, 100% in Trump Tweets

The relevant first percent of their capital will be invested in the S&P500, while the other will be invested on whatever stocks Trump tweets about positively. The way in which we will determine this is that every investor will invest in up to X tweets, where X is the number of tweets they can afford. The amount they will invest will be \$2,000 per tweet. The reason why is that, with our current range and model, the largest amount of tweets we could possibly invest in (assuming positive) is 57, so this will allow Investor #5 to invest all their capital.

# Gives us the next possible day to buy a stock
def get_next_available_day(date, ticker):
    day_change = otherdate.timedelta(days=1)
    dates = stock_tables[ticker].sort_values(by=['date'])['date'].tolist()
    
    date = str(date)[:10]
    date = datetime.strptime(date,'%Y-%m-%d')
    
    date += day_change
    
    while date not in dates:
        date += day_change
        
    return date

# Getting each investors profit per day
def get_profits(stocks, date):
    total = 0
    for key in stocks.keys():
        
        if key != 'can_buy' and key != 'SNP':
            stock_close_price = stock_tables[key].at[date, 'Close']        
            total += (stocks[key] * stock_close_price)
        elif key == 'SNP':
            close_price = sp500_table.at[date, 'Close']
            total += (stocks[key] * close_price)
                
    return total

Part 5: Insight and Conclusion¶

From what we see in our findings and our exploration, there doesn't seem to be a major significant difference between having invested in stocks that were mentioned by Trump and those that weren't.

We defined our margin of error to be 5%, so that if we found that overall we would've made more than 5% more investing in the stocks we found in Trump's tweets, we would determine the null hypothesis to be false.

We did find this was the case, when we invested 20% of our portfolio into the stocks, and the other 80% in the S&P500, we found an edge of a bit over 5%. However, for all other scenarios, the difference was less than 5%. Even more, when investing more than 20%, the returns started to diminish, and even fell below the control (Investor #1) for 100% of the portfolio invested in stocks (Investor #5).

Thus, I would feel confident in saying that we have not been able to disprove the null hypothesis. So, it doesn't seem to be the case that Trump's tweet had an influence in the stock market, or rather, we cannot prove that they didn't.
